**Session ID:** 3b500a5a-2dfa-4050-b17d-c9890f7e109b
**Message #2**

Of course. This is a classic CSS specificity problem, and a very common one when combining `@tailwindcss/typography` with a syntax highlighter like Shiki. Let's debug this.

### The Problem: Style Conflict

The root cause is a direct style conflict between the **`@tailwindcss/typography` plugin** (which powers the `prose` classes) and **Shiki's** generated styles.

1.  **How Shiki Works:** Shiki analyzes your code and wraps different parts (keywords, strings, comments) in `<span>` tags with inline `style="color: #...;"` attributes. This provides the multi-colored syntax highlighting.

2.  **How `@tailwindcss/typography` Works:** The `prose` classes are designed to apply a consistent and beautiful set of styles to a block of markdown content. It has default styles for `p`, `h1`, `blockquote`, and, crucially, for `pre` and `code` elements.

3.  **The Collision:** In your `BlogPost.astro`, you are using `prose-code:text-theme-code-text`. This utility instructs Tailwind to apply a single color (`var(--theme-code-text)`) to all `<code>` elements within the `prose` container. This single, more specific rule from Tailwind overrides all the individual inline color styles that Shiki carefully applied to the `<span>`s inside the code block.

Essentially, Tailwind is painting over Shiki's detailed work with a single coat of paint.

---

### The Solution: Separate Concerns

The solution is to tell the typography plugin to ignore code blocks entirely, letting Shiki have full control over them. We will then use your custom CSS to style the code block's container (the "frame").

Here are the precise steps to fix this:

#### Step 1: Disable Typography's Default Code Styling

Modify your `tailwind.config.js` to prevent the `prose` class from styling `pre` and `code` elements.

**File: `tailwind.config.js`**

```javascript
/** @type {import('tailwindcss').Config} */
module.exports = {
  // ... other config
  theme: {
    extend: {
      // ... your existing extend properties (colors, fonts, etc.)

      // Add this typography configuration to override the defaults
      typography: ({ theme }) => ({
        DEFAULT: {
          css: {
            // This is the key: disable prose styling for code blocks
            'pre': false,
            'code': false,
            'code::before': false,
            'code::after': false,
          },
        },
      }),
    },
  },
  plugins: [
    require('@tailwindcss/typography'),
    // ... your other plugins
  ],
}
```

**Why this works:** By setting `pre` and `code` to `false`, you are explicitly telling `@tailwindcss/typography` *not* to generate its default styles for these tags. This resolves the conflict at its source.

#### Step 2: Clean Up the `BlogPost.astro` Component

Now that `prose` no longer styles code, the utilities for it are unnecessary and were part of the problem. Remove them.

**File: `src/layouts/BlogPost.astro`**

```astro
<!-- BEFORE -->
<div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none ... prose-code:text-theme-code-text prose-code:bg-theme-code-bg ...">
  <slot />
</div>

<!-- AFTER (Corrected) -->
<div class="prose prose-lg max-w-none prose-headings:text-theme-text-primary prose-p:text-theme-text-primary prose-a:text-theme-link hover:prose-a:text-theme-link-hover prose-strong:text-theme-text-primary prose-blockquote:text-theme-text-secondary prose-blockquote:border-theme-border-primary">
  <slot />
</div>
```

#### Step 3: Rely on Your Custom CSS for the Container

Your existing CSS in `theme-tokens.css` is already perfectly set up to style the code block's container. It correctly targets `pre.astro-code` to handle the background, border, and padding without interfering with the text colors inside.

**File: `theme-tokens.css`**

```css
/* This rule is now in full control of the code block's frame. */
pre.astro-code {
  background-color: var(--shiki-color-background) !important;
  color: var(--shiki-color-text) !important; /* This sets the default text color for non-highlighted parts */
  border: 1px solid var(--theme-border-primary);
  border-radius: 0.5rem;
  padding: 1rem;
  overflow-x: auto;
  font-size: 0.875rem;
  line-height: 1.5;
  transition: background-color 0.2s ease-in-out, border-color 0.2s ease-in-out;
}
```
**Note:** After the fix, you can likely remove the `!important` declarations, as the style conflict that required them has been resolved.

After making these changes, **restart your Astro development server** for the `tailwind.config.js` modifications to take effect. Your syntax highlighting should now appear correctly in both light and dark modes.


---
